      <p style="titleMargin">
        <b>Basic Limit Properties</b>
      </p>

      <stack style="questionAnswer">
        <equation>$ \lim_{x\rightarrow c} k = k $</equation>
        <p>The limit of a constant, k, as x approaches c, is the constant k.</p>
      </stack>

      <stack style="questionAnswer">
        <equation>$ \lim_{x\rightarrow c} x = c $</equation>
        <p>When x gets closer and closer to c, x gets closer to c. This is fairly intuitive.</p>
      </stack>

      <stack style="questionAnswer">
        <equation>$ \lim_{x\rightarrow c} [k f(x)] = k \lim_{x\rightarrow c} f(x) $</equation>
        <p>This property means that the limit of a constant times a function is equal to the constant times the limit of a function. </p>
      </stack>

      <stack style="questionAnswer">
        <equation>$ \lim_{x\rightarrow c} [f(x) \pm g(x)] = \lim_{x\rightarrow c} f(x) \pm \lim_{x\rightarrow c} g(x) $</equation>
        <p>The limit of a sum or difference is the sum of or difference of the limits. </p>
      </stack>

      <stack style="questionAnswer">
        <equation>$ \lim_{x\rightarrow c} [f(x) \times g(x)] = \lim_{x\rightarrow c} f(x) \times \lim_{x\rightarrow c} g(x) $</equation>
        <p>The limit of a product is the product of the limits. </p>
      </stack>

      <stack style="questionAnswer">
        <equation>$ \lim_{x\rightarrow c} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \frac{\lim_{x\rightarrow c} f(x)}{\lim_{x\rightarrow c} g(x)}q$</equation>
        <p>The limit of a quotient is the quotient of the limits. </p>
      </stack>

